      <hedline>
        <hl1>Moment of Decision: The Vote on China Trade</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>David Graff letter disputes May 19 Op-Ed article by national security adviser Samuel R Berger and economic adviser Gene Sperling backing normal trade relations with China (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I appreciate the Clinton administration's explanation of why trade with China is necessary (Op-Ed, May 19). Now I wish someone would explain the difference between China and Cuba -- why we wish to trade with one and embargo the other.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I appreciate the Clinton administration's explanation of why trade with China is necessary (Op-Ed, May 19). Now I wish someone would explain the difference between China and Cuba -- why we wish to trade with one and embargo the other.</p>
        <p>Both countries are ruled by Communist dictatorships that oppress their people. Yet we will trade with one hoping that contact with the outside world will reduce ''the government's ability to control workers'' and ''help Chinese citizens seeking new ideas and tools for political activism,'' while we embargo the other to punish and weaken its government.</p>
        <p>DAVID GRAFF  Columbus, Ohio, May 19, 2000</p>
      </block>
